  "why": "The semantic consistency dimension of the metric is not applicable, as the paper's method, ASDF, employs a differential testing oracle which does not assume semantic equivalence between inputs. The naturalness dimension is applicable, as the goal is to test Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) systems with plausible speech. However, the framework does not actively enforce the naturalness of its generated inputs. It uses a filtering mechanism where a mutated input is only considered valid if at least one ASR system can correctly transcribe it. This is a weak proxy for naturalness, as it only filters out inputs that are so distorted that they are indecipherable to all tested systems, rather than ensuring they remain realistic. The method lacks any explicit mechanism to control for cumulative distortion or to validate the realism of the generated audio against the original seed. The authors explicitly acknowledge this limitation, stating that the computer-generated audio may not be interchangeable with real-world human speech, thus allowing potentially unrealistic inputs to induce failures.",
